  "eprint": {
    "title": "Secure Computation over Lattices and Elliptic Curves",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Brett Hemenway Falk",
        "email": "dgnoble@cis",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Daniel Noble",
        "email": "edufbrett@cis",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Traditional threshold cryptosystems have decentralized core cryptographic primitives like key generation, decryption and signatures.\nMost threshold cryptosystems, however, rely on special purpose protocols that cannot easily be integrated into\nmore complex multiparty protocols.\n\nIn this work, we design and implement decentralized versions of\nlattice-based and elliptic-curve-based public-key cryptoystems using\ngeneric secure multiparty computation (MPC) protocols.\nThese are standard cryptosystems, so we introduce no\nadditional work for encrypting devices and no\nnew assumptions beyond those of the generic MPC framework.\nBoth cryptosystems are also additively homomorphic,\nwhich allows for secure additions directly on ciphertexts.\nBy using generic MPC techniques,\nour multiparty decryption protocols compute secret-shares of the plaintext,\nwhereas most special-purpose cryptosystems either do not support decryption\nor must reveal the decryptions in the clear.\nOur method allows complex functions to be securely evaluated after decryption,\nrevealing only the results of the functions and not the plaintexts themselves.\n\nTo improve performance, we present a novel oblivious elliptic curve multiplication\nprotocol and a new noise-masking technique which may be of independent interest.\nWe implemented our protocols using the SCALE-MAMBA secure multiparty computation platform,\nwhich provides security against malicious adversaries and supports arbitrary numbers of participants.",
    "keywords": [
      "distributed cryptography",
      "key management",
      "threshold cryptography",
      "public-key cryptography",
      "lattice techniques",
      "elliptic curve cryptosystem"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
